@kurtbrose I ruthlessly stole your idea of subclassing tuple and extended it a bit more with some metaclass programming. The idea is that you get a custom class based on tuple, but with attributes manufactured from calling Type. Thus each frozendict is a custom generated class with attribute values for each of the hash values of it's keys. Each one of those attributes is a lambda that contains a pointer to the index value of the value which it points to.

This has fast pre-indexed lookups and is truly immutable.

I see what you mean and I think is a pretty interesting feature. I am currently deep into another thing so I will start working on this a bit later (beginning of June?). OFC pull requests are welcome.

In the meantime, you can use this code snippet as a reference for implementing such functionality in you application.

```python
from pebble import concurrent
from multiprocessing import Queue

@concurrent.process(timeout=60)
def worker(queue, url):
    """Processes a URL splitting the report in chunks and putting it in the given Queue."""
    for chunk in process(url):
        queue.put(chunk)

def process(url):
    """A function seemingly producing large data split in chunks."""
    while True:
        yield None
       
queue = Queue()
future = worker(queue, "www.example.com")

while not future.done():
    chunk = queue.get()

if future.exception() is not None:
    print("Error while processing the URL")
```

It appears that instead of using "updateAll", [destroying](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#destroy) tablesorter and reinitializing it works better ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/LkqTU/23781/)):

```js
// include false to prevent tablesorter class name from being removed
$('.tablesorter').trigger("destroy", false);
initializeTable();
```

I've never used knockout js before, so I'm not sure if it's working 100%... I can't seem to remove any of the original 15 rows.

If you look at the [main demo](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-locale-sort.html), it shows how to add more values to the `$.tablesorter.characterEquivalents` reference.

Here is an example ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/r25tag6k/10/))

```js
$.extend($.tablesorter.characterEquivalents, {
  "r": "ř",
  "R": "Ř",
  "s": "š",
  "S": "Š",
  "z": "ž",
  "Z": "Ž"
});
$(function() {
  $("table").tablesorter({
    debug: true,
    theme: 'blue',
    // Enable use of the characterEquivalents reference
    sortLocaleCompare: true
  });
});
```

Alternatively, and maybe a better solution since it sounds like you might be sorting a Czech alphabet... you can switch the sorting algorithm to use Sugar js... see the documentation on sorting the [Czech alphabet](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/wiki/Language#czech).

